    {
      "id": "note-3",
      "title": "Local-First App Security Guidelines",
      "content": "Local-first apps require security boundaries even on host machines. Secure endpoints using Bearer token authentication stored locally. Implement a strict rate-limiting mechanism to avoid denial-of-service attempts by malicious browser extensions. Ensure that user inputs are sanitized of HTML tags and Javascript blocks to prevent Stored XSS. Do not write credentials or API keys directly to public files or Git repositories.",
      "summary": "Security boundaries are essential for local-first applications on host environments. Key guidelines include Bearer token authentication, rate limiting, and inputs sanitization to prevent Stored XSS. Sensitive credentials must be isolated from repository files.",
      "tags": [
        "security",
        "local-first",
        "nodejs",
        "best-practices"
      ],
      "actionItems": [
        "Exclude .env from markdown export functionality",
        "Restrict client-side API token access"
      ],
